Chef Linda: A common description of a “hash” generally involves two words you won’t find here—
meat and eggs. Instead, ground tempeh and a winning combination of fresh vegetables make for a
savory breakfast dish that is just as good. Hash is often made on the stovetop, but we roast ours, not
only to reduce the amount of oil used in frying, but also to deepen and lock in the flavors. Enjoy this
hash alone, as a side dish to our quiche (pg. 37) or Tofu Scramble (pg. 34), or stuffed and roasted in a
bell pepper or acorn squash.
Allergens: Contains soy and ingredients that may contain gluten
Special Equipment: Food processor or box grater
Tip: This hash loves a splash of hot sauce.
